Our work this time uses the data set from the China Air Quality Historical Data Set on July 9, 2021. It focused on analyzing the spatial and temporal distribution patterns of air pollution, the temporal and spatial evolution, and pollution difference. By identifying major pollution sources, analyzing pollution rates, and comparing different cities in the same time period, the data was processed in many aspects, and finally the outcome was the national air pollution visual analysis system, with six different data views.
First, we performed preprocessing operations such as data sorting, data cleaning, data statistics, and AQI level calculation. Analyzed the composition of regional pollutants and main pollution sources. In the process of analyzing data, based on different data granularity, a complete visual analysis system was designed and implemented. We utilized the daily average data analysis page to do visual analysis on the daily average data. Used pollution indicator and weather data map, pollution indicator coil graph, AQI ranking, pollution indicator and AQI parallel coordinates and other views to provide analysis of pollution time and space distribution patterns and time and space evolution; combined with flexible and rich interaction, users are able to use the other pages on this page. The view did a more fine-grained point of interest analysis. The hourly data analysis page mainly used the comparison module to expand the temporal and spatial distribution patterns and evolutionary trends. The design realized the urban air pollution meteorological data loop, which efficiently and accurately represented the multi-dimensional data within a day, and completed the comparative analysis task of multiple cities and dates.
Located in the middle of the environmental visualization system, we can see a national air pollution degree change table that changes over time. As time changes (0-24 o'clock), our statistical data presents different levels of pollution in the system To visualize the data. On the bottom left, colors are used to distinguish six different levels of pollution in an area. Click the pause/play button below to observe the national pollution level map at a specific time in detail, and click the time point directly below to view the national pollution level map at the target time. Click on the province in the center of the big picture, and on the upper left and the small pictures on the upper right, you can view the pollution level map of the designated province at the time and the current province's pollution source analysis radar imaging map.
Highlight the situation and situation of air pollution in a simple way. The evaluation data of air pollution degree is often used to indicate the short-term air quality status and change trend of the city, namely the Air Quality Index (Air Quality Index), abbreviated as AQI, and its peak appears in From 10:00 to 16:00, the geographical position is in the central and eastern part of our country.

The small pictures on the left and right represent different meanings:
1. The data map on the upper left is the pollution degree map of the province currently clicked. Move the mouse to any city in the province you belong to in the small picture on the upper left to display the current city's AQI index and its pollution level.
2. The data graph in the middle on the left is the AQI change curve graph of a single city. It is the change curve of the city's AQI between 0-24 o'clock in Qingdao. The data interval is 1 hour. The line graph is used to visualize the data and display continuous data that changes over time, highlighting the trend of Qingdao's data at equal time intervals.
3. The data chart at the bottom left is the data of different pollution sources in a certain time period in a city, and the pollution source analysis of Qingdao at 15 o'clock. Data includes: PM2.5, PM10, SO2, NO2, O3, CO.
4. The data chart at the bottom right is a comparison chart of PM2.5 in the same city at different time periods. Comparison of PM2.5 in Qingdao, compare the changes of PM2.5 data in Qingdao in different time periods (with an interval of five hours). When the data is close, use a histogram to visualize the data to expand the gap between the performance data and enhance understanding and clarity.
5. The data chart in the middle on the right is the AQI comparison chart of different cities in the same time period. The AQI data comparison of Qingdao, Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Shenzhen at the same time period uses a line graph to visualize the data, showing continuous data that changes over time, highlighting the trend of the data in the above five major cities at equal time intervals. Click the city name above the image to hide/show its data line graph for further comparison and reference.
6. The data map on the upper right is a radar map for the pollution source analysis of the province currently clicked. Data includes: PM2.5, PM10, SO2, NO2, O3, CO.

Finally, in the process of using the system to carry out case analysis, we found that most of the AQI peaks, that is, serious pollution often occurs at noon and afternoon in most cities at the same time, and there is a positive correlation between PM2.5, PM10, SO2, NO2, and CO. O3 and other pollution indicators are mostly negatively correlated, and the correlation with meteorological factors is different in different regions; through the view, some areas with obvious pollution characteristics can be analyzed, and the changes and changes of pollution types can be analyzed based on the actual situation. The reason. At the same time, the frequent haze weather in the Middle East part of China is due to the following reasons.
1. Part of the atmospheric air pressure in the Middle East of China is low, the air is not flowing, and the population density is the main factor. Due to the non-flowing of the air, the tiny particles in the air tend to gather and float in the air.
2. There is more dust on the ground in cities, and the air humidity is low. The flow of people and vehicles on the ground often agitates the dust to float in the air.
3. Automobile exhaust is the main pollutant emission. In recent years, the number of automobiles in developed cities has gradually increased. The number of license plates in major cities is a strong evidence. Automobile exhaust is also a factor of smog.
4. Secondary pollution produced by the factory.
5. Pollutants such as CO2 emitted from heating in winter.
The prevention and control of air pollution is a complex and huge systematic system engineering that requires the joint efforts of individuals, collectives, countries, and even countries around the world. The fundamental way to reduce air pollution is to do everything possible to reduce the emission of pollutants. The specific measures are recommended as follows:
(1) Improve the energy structure and vigorously develop new energy technologies, and try to use pollution-free or low-polluting energy: make full use of energy that is harmless to environmental pollution, such as wind energy, water energy, and solar energy.
(2) Pretreatment of fuel: Desulfurization, denitrification and improvement of the treatment technology (filtration, absorption, cooling, etc.) before exhaust gas emission.
(3) Vigorously carry out tree planting and afforestation activities to improve the self-purification ability of the environment.
(4) Improve the process technology of high energy-consuming and high-polluting enterprises such as chemical industry, metallurgy, steel, cement, etc., and strictly formulate and implement industrial policies to control air pollution, and introduce a series of industrial industry policy standards to prevent heavy pollution.
(5) Compound pollution is now beginning to appear. After PM2.5 is treated to a certain level, ozone will still rise. In the future, the focus of atmospheric treatment can gradually shift to compound pollution.



